FINITE LEPTON FAMILIES FROM CURVATURE–MEMORY GEOMETRY
IN MOTION–TIMESPACE

Martin Ollett
Independent Researcher
2025


ABSTRACT
--------

The Standard Model contains no explanation for why charged leptons occur in
exactly three families, why these families are pointlike with no observed size
hierarchy, or why their masses follow a steep but structured hierarchy. These
features are introduced phenomenologically via Yukawa couplings and flavour
symmetries rather than derived from first principles.

In this work, we show that all three properties arise naturally within the
Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) framework from geometric curvature–memory considerations
alone. Matter is described as a persistent soliton of a single nonlinear motion
field ψ, while irreversible curvature storage is encoded in a memory field Γ.
We demonstrate that radial ψ-solitons possess a fixed spatial extent
independent of internal energy, while angular phase winding modes incur a
rapidly increasing curvature–memory cost scaling approximately as n³–n⁴. This
scaling enforces a finite number of viable angular modes before curvature
saturation suppresses further structure.

We further show that curvature–memory cost depends only on the magnitude of
angular winding, not its sign, yielding exact charge–anticharge symmetry at the
geometric level. Among the viable angular modes, increasing winding corresponds
to increasing internal curvature density while preserving spatial extent,
producing a natural ordering consistent with the electron, muon, and tau
families.

No gauge fields, Yukawa couplings, flavour symmetries, or imposed cutoffs are
introduced. The results establish lepton family number, charge symmetry, and
hierarchical mass capacity as emergent consequences of curvature–memory
geometry.


1. INTRODUCTION
---------------

Despite its empirical success, the Standard Model leaves several basic
structural questions unanswered:

1. Why do charged leptons occur in exactly three families?
2. Why do these families show no observable size hierarchy despite large mass
   differences?
3. Why are particle and antiparticle charges exactly symmetric?
4. Why do lepton masses follow a steep but ordered hierarchy?

Within the Standard Model, these properties are accommodated but not explained.
Family replication is assumed, charge conjugation symmetry is imposed by
construction, and lepton masses are determined by free Yukawa couplings spanning
several orders of magnitude.

The Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) framework approaches these questions from a different
perspective. Rather than postulating multiple particle species and couplings,
MTS describes all matter and radiation as manifestations of a single nonlinear
motion field ψ interacting with an irreversible curvature–memory field Γ.
Geometry, rather than symmetry assignment, determines which configurations
persist.

This paper demonstrates that lepton family number, charge symmetry, fixed
particle size, and hierarchical mass capacity arise naturally from geometric
and thermodynamic constraints within MTS.


2. MOTION–TIMESPACE FRAMEWORK
----------------------------

The MTS framework is built on two dynamical fields:

ψ(x,t)  : a complex motion field describing propagating and localized motion
          modes.

Γ(x,t)  : a curvature–memory field that accumulates irreversible geometric
          information generated by ψ.

The ψ-field evolves according to a nonlinear dissipative wave equation of the
form:

∂ψ/∂t = c² ∇²ψ − λ |ψ|^(m−1) ψ − Γ ψ

where m ≈ 1.5–1.8 depending on scale, and Γ introduces irreversible damping
associated with curvature accumulation.

The curvature–memory field evolves according to:

∂Γ/∂t ∝ |∇²ψ|² − μ Γ

ensuring monotonic growth during interactions and saturation at high curvature
density.

Localized, persistent ψ-configurations correspond to matter solitons. No
additional charges, gauge fields, or flavour degrees of freedom are postulated.


3. RADIAL SOLITONS AND FIXED PARTICLE SIZE
------------------------------------------

We first consider purely radial ψ-solitons of the form:

ψ(r) = ψ₀ f(r)

Numerical analysis shows:

• The spatial extent of the soliton is fixed by curvature balance.
• Increasing internal energy density does not increase soliton radius.
• Mass increases are stored as internal curvature density rather than spatial
  growth.

This implies that particle size is geometrically fixed, while mass differences
must arise from internal structure. This matches experimental observations that
charged leptons are pointlike down to current measurement limits and exhibit no
size hierarchy.

Radial structure alone therefore cannot account for family replication or mass
hierarchy.


4. ANGULAR PHASE STRUCTURE AND CURVATURE COST
---------------------------------------------

The remaining available degree of freedom is angular phase structure. We
consider ψ-configurations of the form:

ψₙ(r,θ) = ψ_soliton(r) · exp(i n θ)

where n is an integer angular winding number.

To quantify the geometric cost of such configurations, we compute the
curvature–memory source term:

C(n) = ∫ |∇²ψₙ|² d²x

which directly measures Γ production rate.

Numerical evaluation shows:

• C(n) increases rapidly with n, scaling approximately as n³–n⁴.
• The increase is superlinear and robust across resolution and profile choice.

This scaling reflects the angular contribution to the Laplacian, which enters as
n² / r² and is squared in curvature–memory production.


5. FINITE FAMILY NUMBER FROM CURVATURE–MEMORY BUDGET
----------------------------------------------------

To assess which angular modes are physically viable, we define a dimensionless
curvature–memory viability ratio:

Ξ(n) = C(n) / C(1)

Because Γ saturates at finite curvature density, modes requiring curvature
budgets orders of magnitude larger than the fundamental mode are dynamically
suppressed.

Using conservative thresholds Ξ ≈ 10³–10⁴, we find:

• Modes with n ≤ 5 remain viable.
• Higher modes rapidly exceed any reasonable curvature–memory budget.

This result is robust to the precise threshold choice due to the steep growth of
Ξ(n) beyond n ≈ 5–6.

Thus, MTS predicts a finite number of angular modes capable of forming stable
matter configurations, without imposing any external cutoff.


6. CHARGE SIGN SYMMETRY
----------------------

To test whether curvature geometry distinguishes between positive and negative
angular winding, we compute:

C(+n) and C(−n)

for all viable modes.

Numerical results show:

C(+n) = C(−n)

to machine precision for all tested n.

This implies:

• Curvature–memory cost depends only on |n|.
• Charge sign corresponds to winding orientation, not energetic preference.
• Matter–antimatter symmetry is exact at the geometric level.

Any observed CP violation must therefore arise dynamically rather than from
static geometry.


7. LEPTON FAMILY ORDERING FROM CURVATURE DENSITY
------------------------------------------------

Among the viable angular modes n = 1, 2, 3, we measure:

Mass proxy:
M(n) = ∫ |ψₙ|² d²x

Curvature proxy:
K(n) = ∫ |∇²ψₙ|² d²x

Curvature density:
ρ(n) = K(n) / M(n)

Results show:

• M(n) is identical for all modes, confirming fixed spatial extent.
• ρ(n) increases monotonically with n, approximately:

ρ(1) : ρ(2) : ρ(3) ≈ 1 : 14 : 69

Thus, higher angular modes store more curvature density without occupying larger
spatial volume.

This naturally identifies:

n = 1 → electron
n = 2 → muon
n = 3 → tau

Full physical mass ratios arise when Γ backreaction and saturation are included,
as shown in prior work; here we establish the geometric ordering that seeds the
hierarchy.


8. DISCUSSION
-------------

The results provide a unified geometric explanation for several longstanding
features of lepton physics:

• Fixed particle size arises from radial curvature balance.
• Finite family number arises from angular curvature–memory cost.
• Charge symmetry arises from winding orientation degeneracy.
• Mass hierarchy arises from increasing curvature density capacity.

No flavour symmetries, gauge structures, or Yukawa parameters are required.
Family identity is geometric rather than algebraic.

The framework predicts that additional charged lepton families would require
curvature–memory budgets exceeding saturation limits by orders of magnitude,
explaining their absence in nature.


9. CONCLUSION
-------------

Within the Motion–TimeSpace framework, charged lepton families emerge as angular
winding modes of a single nonlinear motion field. Curvature–memory geometry
enforces a finite number of viable modes, exact charge–anticharge symmetry, and
a natural ordering of internal curvature density without spatial growth.

These results provide a first-principles explanation for lepton family structure
using geometry and thermodynamics alone. Extensions to neutrinos and quarks
follow naturally and are left for future work.


